Yes. Here is the clean way to read the **7-speed W7A-700** layout.

## Big picture

This transmission is basically:

* a **front compound stage** that the book describes as an **inverse Ravigneaux set**
* followed by a **rear simple planetary set**
* followed by a **middle simple planetary set**
* with the **output taken from the carrier of the middle set**

So power goes **left to right** through three stages.

In the core-based model we built, the front inverse-Ravigneaux was represented by an equivalent reusable-core abstraction, but the **functional connections** are the same idea:

* the front stage creates the first level of ratio transformation
* that front-stage result feeds the rear set
* the rear set feeds the middle set
* the middle carrier is the output

---

## What is connected to what

Using the names from `seven_speed.py`, the rotating members are:

* `input` = turbine / transmission input
* `F.sunA` = one controllable member of the front compound stage
* `F.ringB` = the other controllable member of the front compound stage
* `F.car` = front-stage carrier
* `R.sun` = rear set sun
* `R.car` = rear set carrier
* `M.sun` = middle set sun
* `Out` = middle set carrier / output shaft

Now the important permanent mechanical links are:

### 1) Input drives the front stage

The transmission input goes into the **front compound stage**.

In the abstraction we used:

* one front mesh is driven from the input on its ring side
* the other front mesh is driven from the input on its sun side

That is how we emulate the behavior of the inverse Ravigneaux without leaving the reusable core framework.

---

### 2) The front carrier feeds the rear ring

This is one of the most important links:

* **front carrier = rear ring**

In the script that is:

* `F.car` feeds the rear set ring

So whatever speed the front stage produces at its carrier becomes the input to the **rear planetary ring**.

---

### 3) The rear carrier feeds the middle ring

This is the next cascade link:

* **rear carrier = middle ring**

In the script:

* `R.car` is directly tied to the ring of the middle set

So the rear set does not drive the output directly.
Instead, it drives the **middle ring**, and then the middle set performs the final ratio action.

---

### 4) The middle carrier is the output shaft

This is the final output connection:

* **middle carrier = output shaft**

So the output of the whole transmission is taken from the **carrier of the middle planetary set**.

This is why the middle set is always the last stage in the kinematic chain.

---

### 5) C3 ties the rear sun and middle sun together

This is a very important cross-link:

* **C3 connects rear sun to middle sun**

So when C3 is applied, the rear sun and middle sun rotate together as one member.

That means the rear and middle sets become strongly coupled through their sun gears.

This is one of the key tricks of the mechanism.

---

### 6) C2 ties the input to the rear-car/middle-ring node

Another major cross-link:

* **C2 connects input to rear carrier / middle ring**

Since rear carrier and middle ring are already the same node, C2 effectively ties:

* input
* rear carrier
* middle ring

When C2 is on, that whole node is driven at input speed.

This is why upper gears and direct drive become possible.

---

### 7) C1 ties the input to a front-stage control member

C1 acts on the front compound stage:

* **C1 connects input to the controllable front member `F.sunA`**

That causes part of the front stage to lock up with the input instead of being held by a brake.

This changes the behavior of the front stage and moves the transmission into different forward ratios.

---

### 8) The brakes ground specific members

The brakes are what make the planetary sets actually ratio.

They do this:

* **B1** grounds one front-stage control member (`F.sunA`)
* **B3** grounds the other front-stage control member (`F.ringB`)
* **B2** grounds the middle sun (`M.sun`)
* **BR** grounds the rear-car / middle-ring node

So the brakes do not “add power.”
They create the reaction points that force the gearsets to ratio.

---

## The whole chain in one sentence

The easiest way to understand the W7A-700 is:

> The front compound stage creates an intermediate speed at its carrier, that drives the rear ring; the rear carrier then drives the middle ring; the rear sun and middle sun can be tied together by C3; and the output is taken from the middle carrier.

That is the backbone of the mechanism.

---

## Why the front stage is harder to read in the book

The front stage is the confusing part because it is **not a simple planetary** like the other two.

The book says it is an **inverse Ravigneaux set**, which means:

* one sun gear
* two ring gears
* a compound planet arrangement
* shared carrier structure

That makes the drawing much harder to visually parse than a normal simple set.

So the confusion is not on you.
Those diagrams are much harder than the ordinary Simpson or Lepelletier-style sketches.

---

## How the forward gears are created

Here is the functional logic of the shift elements.

### 1st: `C3 + B2 + B3`

* B3 grounds one front-stage control member
* B2 grounds the middle sun
* C3 ties rear sun to middle sun

Effect:

* front stage ratios strongly
* rear and middle are both active
* very large reduction

That is why 1st is the deepest ratio.

---

### 2nd: `C3 + B1 + B2`

* now B1 is the front-stage reaction instead of B3
* B2 still grounds middle sun
* C3 still ties rear and middle suns

Effect:

* front-stage behavior changes
* rear/middle coupling remains
* less reduction than 1st

---

### 3rd: `C1 + C3 + B2`

* C1 now locks part of the front stage to input
* C3 still ties rear and middle suns
* B2 still grounds middle sun

Effect:

* the front stage is no longer reacting through a brake in the same way
* ratio gets closer to 1

---

### 4th: `C1 + C2 + B2`

* C1 locks front control member to input
* C2 drives the rear-car / middle-ring node from input
* B2 grounds middle sun

Effect:

* the rear set is effectively carried along
* the middle set alone provides the remaining reduction
* this is why 4th is closer to direct

---

### 5th: `C1 + C2 + C3`

* C1 on
* C2 on
* C3 on
* no reaction brake in the working path

Effect:

* all the key nodes are locked together
* transmission goes to **direct drive**
* ratio = 1.00

This is the easiest one to understand.

---

### 6th: `C2 + C3 + B1`

* C2 drives rear-car / middle-ring from input
* C3 ties rear sun to middle sun
* B1 grounds the front control member

Effect:

* the coupled rear/middle structure now produces overdrive

---

### 7th: `C2 + C3 + B3`

* same upper-gear structure as 6th
* but front-stage reaction changes from B1 to B3

Effect:

* even more overdrive

---

## How reverse works

### R1: `C3 + B3 + BR`

* C3 ties rear sun to middle sun
* B3 grounds one front-stage member
* BR grounds the rear-car / middle-ring node

Effect:

* the rear/middle train is forced into reverse kinematics
* output rotates backward

### R2: `C3 + B1 + BR`

* same idea as R1, but the front-stage reaction member changes

Effect:

* second reverse ratio

---

## The three most important permanent nodes to remember

If you remember only three hard connections, remember these:

1. **Front carrier → Rear ring**
2. **Rear carrier → Middle ring**
3. **Middle carrier → Output**

And then one important clutch link:

4. **C3 ties Rear sun ↔ Middle sun**

That alone lets you mentally reconstruct most of the transmission.

---

## Why our core model was able to match it

Because even though the front stage drawing is ugly, the mechanism still reduces to a small number of kinematic facts:

* the front stage has two independently controllable members and one shared carrier
* that shared carrier feeds the rear set
* the rear set feeds the middle set
* the rear and middle suns can be tied together
* the output is the middle carrier

That is exactly the kind of thing the reusable solver can handle once the member relationships are identified correctly.

